        </ol>
    </p>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application (10 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_g4r47q7r">
            Direct students to the worked examples in the textbook. Students should work through each example with teacher guidance before attempting the exercises independently.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_on82bmad">
            <em>Teacher prompts:</em>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_hs0kgo5u">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_m9fqehmj"><p xml:id="auto_ey0t6pkm"><q>What are the two parallel sides (bases) of this trapezium?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_y8ipezkc"><p xml:id="auto_dur4ojzz"><q>How do we find the height?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_hkgnjmbf"><p xml:id="auto_7poobwq1"><q>Why do we take the average of the two bases?</q></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_l6tygcqt"><p xml:id="auto_c2k7veg8"><q>How can we use coordinate geometry to find the lengths of the bases?</q></p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_vve1kggt">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_kri3xt8k">
                A trapezium has parallel sides of lengths 
                <m>14 \, \text{cm}</m> and <m>8 \, \text{cm}</m>. 
                The non-parallel sides are each <m>5 \, \text{cm}</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_ov3xcl1h">
                Calculate the area of the trapezium.
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_lrr889nv">
                <ol marker="Step 1:">
                    <li xml:id="auto_5qxkwvuo">
                        <p xml:id="auto_hil4pn51">
                            Sketch and analyse the trapezium.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_hqvj7hqt">
                            Since the non-parallel sides are equal (each <m>5 \, \text{cm}</m>), the trapezium is isosceles.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_ld1yncf5">
                            The difference between the parallel sides is:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_psuhxp4z">
                            <m>14 - 8 = 6 \, \text{cm}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_fn49bv4m">
                            This difference is shared equally on both sides:
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_psh7se9r">
                            <m>\frac{6}{2} = 3 \, \text{cm}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_8xxt7hmx">
                        <p xml:id="auto_7ck9a9lc">
                            Find the height using Pythagoras' Theorem.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_g421hue7">
                            Consider one of the right triangles formed.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_5qdxa5ct">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> h^2 + 3^2 =  5^2</mrow>
                                <mrow> h^2 + 9 = 25 </mrow>
                                <mrow> h^2 = 16 </mrow>
                                <mrow> h = 4 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                            </md>
                            
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_gpxz1hej">
                        <p xml:id="auto_yjtkiq4b">
                            Apply the trapezium area formula.
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_h91pcmxe">
                            <md>
                                <mrow> A = \frac{1}{2} (a + b)h </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \frac{1}{2} (14 + 8) \times 4 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = \frac{1}{2} (22) \times 4 </mrow>
                                <mrow> = 44 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                            </md>
                            
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>


    <example xml:id="auto_thslx7j3">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_0orapoci">
                Calculate the area of the figure below.
            </p>
            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="trapezium">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define the trapezium vertices with the longest side at the bottom
                    \coordinate (A) at (-2,2);
                    \coordinate (B) at (2,2);
                    \coordinate (C) at (3,-1);
                    \coordinate (D) at (-4,-1);
                    
                    % Fill the trapezium with pink color
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Draw the trapezium with thick pink outline
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                    % Find the correct foot of the perpendicular from B to base CD
                    \coordinate (H) at (-2,-1); % Adjusted to be directly below B
                    
                    % Draw perpendicular height from B to base C-D
                    \draw[dotted, thick] (A) -- (H);
                    
                    % Mark the right angle with a visible square at H towards its right
                    \draw[thick] (H) ++(0,0) -- ++(0,0.3) -- ++(0.3,0) -- ++(0,-0.3) -- cycle;
                    % Label the vertices with units
                    \node[above left] at (A) {A (-2,3)};
                    \node[above right] at (B) {B (2,3)};
                    \node[below right] at (C) {C (3,-1)};
                    \node[below left] at (D) {D (-3,-1)};
                    \node[below] at (H) {H (2,-1)};
                    
                    % Label the height
                    \node at (-1.5,0) {4 cm};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_qek5hv9q">
               The given figure is a trapezium with the following vertices: 
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_5vp3yfsw">
                <ul xml:id="auto_1vw13rtf">
                    <li xml:id="auto_4dsi9via">
                        <p xml:id="auto_9rpitjh5">
                          <m>  A(-2,3)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_84c34gdz">
                        <p xml:id="auto_v3l8h6jb">
                            <m>B(2,3)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_vfirx6aj">
                        <p xml:id="auto_pcmd2tc1">
                            <m>C(3,-1)</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_kbbkh2f6">
                        <p xml:id="auto_2f3lnhj2">
                            <m>D(-3,-1)</m>
                        </p>
                         <p xml:id="auto_hy9rd6o6">
                          From the diagram, we observe:
                         </p> 
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_csohqrzi">
                        <p xml:id="auto_a4bia6p0">
                            The two parallel bases are ABAB and DCDC.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_9q0y51i6">
                        <p xml:id="auto_36xzz99g">
                            The height is given as 4 cm, which is the perpendicular distance between the parallel bases.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_o44exmdh">
                Step 1: Determine the lengths of the bases
            </p>
           <p xml:id="auto_5fpqtc5h">
            Length of <m>AB:</m>
            <md>
                <mrow>AB =  |x_1-x_2| \amp = |2-(-2)| = |2+2| = 4 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
            </md>
            Length of <m>DC:</m>
            <md>
                <mrow>DC =  |x_1-x_2| \amp = |3-(-3)| = |3+3| = 6 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
            </md>
           </p>
           <p xml:id="auto_g0ql7law">
            Step 2: Use the trapezium area formula.
            </p>  
            <p xml:id="auto_pvtkjcxi">
              The area of a trapezium is given by:
              <md>
                <mrow>\text{Area} = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times (\text{Base}_1 + \text{Base}_2)  \times \text{Height}</mrow>
              </md>
              Substituting the values:
              <md>
                <mrow>A = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times (4+6) \, \text{cm} \times 4 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times 10 \, \text{cm} \times 4 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                <mrow> =  \amp 20 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
              </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_9r6l7yfl">
                THe area of the trapezium is <m>20 \, \text{cm}^2</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment (5 minutes)</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_wgrdh5ka">
            Students complete the following exit ticket questions individually.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_65n3m6g8">
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_f0dy7tnr"><p xml:id="auto_voij2rf6">A trapezium has a height of 5 cm, the top base is 8 cm and the bottom base is 14 cm. Find its area.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_4yli1utb"><p xml:id="auto_hh4osggc">The bases of a trapezium are 12 cm and 6 cm and its area is <m>45 \text{ cm}^2</m>. Find the height.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_1vxfzmsr"><p xml:id="auto_vgautob5">Find the missing angle in a trapezium where three angles are <m>70^\circ</m>, <m>85^\circ</m> and <m>95^\circ</m>.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_89a5az7l"><p xml:id="auto_ac44o56d">A trapezium-shaped farm has a shorter base of 150 m, a longer base of 300 m and a height of 200 m. Find the area of the farm.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_kxwdofp3"><p xml:id="auto_99oekm0s">A car window is shaped like a trapezium with a height of 50 cm, the top base is 60 cm and the bottom base is 80 cm. Find the area of the window.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_mnibad0d">
            <em>Answer Key:</em>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_gm8yk88w">
            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li xml:id="auto_bl1keogs"><p xml:id="auto_3qdwjy0g"><m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2}(8 + 14) \times 5 = 55 \text{ cm}^2</m></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_atd3fq2y"><p xml:id="auto_p37ly6de"><m>45 = \frac{1}{2}(12 + 6) \times h \Rightarrow 45 = 9h \Rightarrow h = 5 \text{ cm}</m></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_vcwdfos5"><p xml:id="auto_u74p7zzu">Missing angle <m>= 360^\circ - (70^\circ + 85^\circ + 95^\circ) = 110^\circ</m></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_dk26gsd1"><p xml:id="auto_obgae2nz"><m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2}(150 + 300) \times 200 = 45{,}000 \text{ m}^2</m></p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_l2m9yior"><p xml:id="auto_l99lw7ss"><m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2}(60 + 80) \times 50 = 3{,}500 \text{ cm}^2</m></p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <exercises xml:id="exercises-area-of-trapeziums">
        <title>Exercises</title>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-trapezium-height-5-bases-8-14">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_z0kk56sh">
                    A trapezium has a height of <m>5</m> cm, the top base is <m>8</m> cm and the bottom base is <m>14</m> cm. Find its area.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                    <latex-image label="borders-trapezia">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \draw [thick](0,0) coordinate (S)-- (2,4) coordinate (P)-- (7,4) coordinate (Q)-- (10,0) 
                            coordinate (R)-- (7,0) coordinate (T)-- (0,0) coordinate (S);
                            \node at (0,-0.5){S};
                            \node at (2,4.5){P};
                            \node at (7,4.5){Q};
                            \node at (10,-0.5){R};
                            \node at (7,-0.5){T};
                            \node at (7.5,2){5 cm};
                            \node at (5,4.5){8 cm};
                            \node at (5,-0.7){14 cm};
                            \draw [dashed] (7,4) --(7,0);
                            \draw(7,0) coordinate (A)-- (7,0.5) coordinate (B)-- (7.5,0.5) coordinate (C)-- (7.5,0) coordinate(D)-- (7,0) coordinate (A);
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_68szmgd7">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Area} \amp = \frac{1}{2}(a + b) \times h</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2}(8 + 14) \times 5</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2} \times 22 \times 5</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 55 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-trapezium-find-height">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_djcx8k1y">
                    The bases of a trapezium are 12 cm and 6 cm and its area is <m>45 \, \text{cm}^2</m>. Find the height.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                    <latex-image label="borders-quadrilateral">
                        \begin{tikzpicture}
                            \draw [thick](0,0) coordinate (S)-- (2,4) coordinate (P)-- (7,4) coordinate (Q)-- (10,0) 
                            coordinate (R)-- (7,0) coordinate (T)-- (0,0) coordinate (S);
                            \node at (0,-0.5){S};
                            \node at (2,4.5){P};
                            \node at (7,4.5){Q};
                            \node at (10,-0.5){R};
                            \node at (7,-0.5){T};
                            \node at (7.5,2){h};
                            \node at (5,4.5){6 cm};
                            \node at (5,-0.7){12 cm};
                            \node at (4,2){$A=45 \text{ cm}^2$};
                            \draw [dashed] (7,4) --(7,0);
                            \draw(7,0) coordinate (A)-- (7,0.5) coordinate (B)-- (7.5,0.5) coordinate (C)-- (7.5,0) coordinate(D)-- (7,0) coordinate (A);
                        \end{tikzpicture}
                    </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_5dshticg">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>45 \amp = \frac{1}{2}(12 + 6) \times h</mrow>
                        <mrow>45 \amp = \frac{1}{2} \times 18 \times h</mrow>
                        <mrow>45 \amp = 9h</mrow>
                        <mrow>h \amp = 5 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-trapezium-missing-angle">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_u1951ly9">
                    Find the missing angle in a trapezium where three angles are <m>70^\circ</m>, <m>85^\circ</m> and <m>95^\circ</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_0bmjttnn">
                    The sum of interior angles of any quadrilateral is <m>360^\circ</m>.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Missing angle} \amp = 360^\circ - (70^\circ + 85^\circ + 95^\circ)</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 360^\circ - 250^\circ</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 110^\circ</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-trapezium-isosceles">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_b1w6515a">
                    A trapezium has equal non-parallel sides (legs). What special type of trapezium is this?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_lsomw3kx">
                    A trapezium with equal non-parallel sides (legs) is called an <em>isosceles trapezium</em>. Its base angles are equal and its diagonals are equal in length.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-trapezium-bases-20-30">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_3enbyixj">
                    The parallel sides of a trapezium are 20 m and 30 m and its height is 12 m. Find its area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_fj6uozo9">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Area} \amp = \frac{1}{2}(a + b) \times h</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2}(20 + 30) \times 12</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2} \times 50 \times 12</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 300 \, \text{m}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-trapezium-farm">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_5ozkrfng">
                    A trapezium-shaped farm has a shorter base of 150 m, a longer base of 300 m and a height of 200 m. Find the area of the farm.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_gg0zytyj">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Area} \amp = \frac{1}{2}(a + b) \times h</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2}(150 + 300) \times 200</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2} \times 450 \times 200</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 45{,}000 \, \text{m}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-trapezium-car-window">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_8yxwn8wy">
                    A car window is shaped like a trapezium with a height of 50 cm, the top base is 60 cm and the bottom base is 80 cm. Find the area of the window.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_1jd2m16o">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Area} \amp = \frac{1}{2}(a + b) \times h</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2}(60 + 80) \times 50</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2} \times 140 \times 50</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 3{,}500 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="ex-trapezium-table">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_0r99hbvk">
                    A trapezoidal table has a top base of 1.2 m, a bottom base of 1.8 m and a height of 0.75 m. What is its surface area?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_ja3c59yj">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Area} \amp = \frac{1}{2}(a + b) \times h</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2}(1.2 + 1.8) \times 0.75</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = \frac{1}{2} \times 3.0 \times 0.75</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 1.125 \, \text{m}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_4rf2q4a4">
            <em>For Struggling Learners:</em>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_29tc6j4p">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_oej6spdv"><p xml:id="auto_o8tz0mgg">Provide pre-drawn trapeziums with bases and height already labelled.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_4spi4gm2"><p xml:id="auto_h1u2mgiy">Use simpler numbers for base lengths and heights.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_vn31fc7s"><p xml:id="auto_grys519c">Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_uvr87w57"><p xml:id="auto_cr4khc75">Provide step-by-step calculation templates.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_czok4uza"><p xml:id="auto_6pulwtyb">Allow use of calculators.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ftqbnkxt">
            <em>For On-Level Learners:</em>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_qd5sqp7i">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_2wykiqkm"><p xml:id="auto_pt32q31p">Encourage students to draw their own trapeziums from word problems.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3g0iehvw"><p xml:id="auto_809ftqep">Ask students to explain which formula they chose and why.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_t4cbanu3"><p xml:id="auto_glbjleb2">Provide mixed practice with both finding area and finding missing dimensions.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_nl67jniv">
            <em>For Advanced Learners:</em>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_0aui5tpa">
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_67guecki"><p xml:id="auto_8ye044j7">Challenge students to derive the formula themselves using the concept of average bases.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_w7gigoq9"><p xml:id="auto_drhj84l4">Explore real-world applications: architecture, bridge design, furniture design.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_b427arpf"><p xml:id="auto_q7h5ylm7">Investigate the relationship between the area of a trapezium and other quadrilaterals.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_6jsymunb"><p xml:id="auto_azikvj3s">Apply the formula to find missing base lengths or height when area is known.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Extension Activity</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_y6mitc31">
            <em>Real-World Application: Designing Trapezium-Shaped Structures</em>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_zweb7yqj">
            Students work in groups to design a trapezium-shaped structure (bridge, table, window, farm) and calculate its area.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_hf5ebi8l">
            Materials: Graph paper, rulers, protractors, calculators, coloured pencils.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_xybnvsok">
            Tasks:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_2mom6gke">
            <ol>
                <li xml:id="auto_k34puqmb"><p xml:id="auto_x2l6j4t6">Choose a real-world application that uses trapezium shapes.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_pc1ywhx1"><p xml:id="auto_hciuzjig">Draw the trapezium on graph paper with appropriate dimensions.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_4n0g3sl0"><p xml:id="auto_jnwl35u1">Measure or specify the lengths of both bases and the height.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_sphb67lg"><p xml:id="auto_pnvqlqwp">Calculate the area using the formula <m>\text{Area} = \frac{1}{2}(a + b) \times h</m>.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_eaq09xug"><p xml:id="auto_fw339lft">Present your findings to the class, explaining your design choices and calculations.</p></li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </axiom>

